sentences: Andy Narell (born March 18, 1954) is an American jazz steel pannist, composer and producer.

Beginning in 1962, Andy, his brother Jeff, and three others boys played on a third set of Sterling-made pans in the basement of the Narell house in the Whitestone neighborhood of Queens, calling themselves the Steel Bandits.
The band was a novelty steelpan act that played concerts and appeared on television shows, including I've Got a Secret in 1963.
Murray Narell invited Ellie Mannette in 1964 to expand steelpan activities in New York City and convinced him to come in 1967.
Murray Narell invited Ellie Mannette in 1964 to expand steelpan activities in New York City and convinced him to come in 1967.
He started the record label Hip Pocket and released his first solo album, Hidden Treasures, in 1979.
With an interest in Caribbean music, Latin jazz, and rhythm and blues, he joined the Caribbean Jazz Project in 1995 with Dave Samuels and Paquito D'Rivera.
Narell performed in South Africa in 1999 in front of a crowd of 80,000 people.

In 1999 Narrell became the first foreigner to compose for Panorama steel band competition in Trinidad, guiding the 100-player Skiffle Bunch Steel Orchestra to the finals of both the 1999 and 2000 Panoramas.

After a 12 year hiatus, Narell returned to Panorama in 2013 and the subsequent three years to arrange for Birdsong.

His arrangements have continued to introduce musical ideas that have not been done before in Panorama, such as the 6/8 time in a section of "We Kinda Music" in 2014.
